@flexiarg plos-npt-with-small-n/venue-register-boundary
@title Use Content Cousins for Positioning, Not Venue Register
@keywords venue-register, literature-positioning, PLOS, BMC, content-cousin, model-paper
@audience paper authors, literature-reviewers, drafters
@tone technical
@style pattern
@source-dois [10.1186/s12913-019-4398-1 10.1186/s12913-021-06977-1 10.1371/journal.pone.0239181 10.1371/journal.pone.0195890]
@references [plos-npt-with-small-n/framework-spine-with-empirical-ribs plos-npt-with-small-n/training-role-feature-register]

! conclusion: Papers outside PLOS ONE can be content cousins without being register models.  Use BMC train-the-trainer or implementation studies to position the literature, vocabulary, and intervention family; use PLOS ONE papers to model abstract structure, Methods granularity, tables, headings, and claim scope.

  + context: The BMC STORM and DEALTS2 papers are close content cousins for cascade training, train-the-trainer design, implementation barriers, and NPT-informed analysis.  They are useful for literature positioning.  But the requested library is about PLOS-with-small-n presentation, so the venue register should be drawn primarily from PLOS ONE exemplars.

  + IF:
    The pattern operates on the axis: topical similarity <-> venue-style suitability.
    Irreducible: a paper can be substantively close but rhetorically mismatched.  Content evidence and venue emulation are different jobs.

  + HOWEVER:
    Real costs: separating content cousins from register models means extra discipline in drafting: a useful article may be cited heavily while not being copied structurally.  This can feel artificial when the cousin is the closest intervention match.
    Active dynamic: authors naturally imitate the paper that feels closest to their topic.  Reviewers, however, respond to the target venue's presentation norms.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - Cousin-as-template: a non-PLOS article supplies the section shape, table density, or discussion style for a PLOS submission.
      - Venue-register-blindness: all cited papers are treated as equally useful models.
      - Literature-gap-overfit: the Introduction positions against the closest cousin but ignores PLOS exemplars that establish acceptable small-n presentation.
      - Methods-style-import: another venue's looser or denser Methods conventions are imported without checking PLOS fit.

  + THEN: Assign each exemplar a job.
    + COMPOSITIONS:
      (1) Source-role table.
          Columns: paper, venue, content role, register role, use in draft.
          Effect: prevents accidental imitation of the wrong model.
      (2) PLOS-primary structure pass.
          Schema: {:abstract <PLOS model> :methods <PLOS model> :results <PLOS model> :lit-positioning <content cousins>}
          Effect: preserves target-venue fit.
      (3) Cousin citation boundary.
          Schema: "We cite <cousin> for <intervention/literature point>, not as a structural precedent."
          Effect: makes the drafting discipline explicit.

    + CHECK:
      Engaged when each exemplar has a declared role: register model, methods ammunition, content cousin, or positioning source.  Failing when the draft borrows structure from the closest topical paper regardless of venue.
